A year ago today I was in Tam Dao, Vietnam at the @animalsasia sanctuary learning about the senseless cruelty of the bear bile industry. Thanks to 25 years of steadfast commitment and determination, Animals Asia has helped bring a permanent end to this heinous trade in Vietnam. This year a second bear sanctuary will be up and running in Bach Ma with the mission of caring for all remaining bears that are currently being surrendered and rescued from bile farms. There will not be a single bear left behind to suffer. I don’t quite have the words to express just how momentous this achievement is but I will never forget the impact these bears have had on me and how truly moved I am that there are people like Jill Robinson in the world. Please consider donating.  If you are interested and want to learn more got to www.animalsasia.org

I will never forget hearing Sinéad O’Connor for the first time.  I was 15 when “Nothing Compares 2 U” came out and it was a time when every minute of my existence felt fragile.  The depth of feeling, pain and longing in Sinéad’s voice all wrapped in her sharp and wild beauty, took my breath away. 

Her voice encompassed the world and shot me straight in the heart. 

Then she spoke up, ripped that photo of the Pope in half…  I’ll never forget that moment either because I was afraid for her.  She made “sensible” ladies gasp and pitiful men rage and she was undoubtably pushing where others would not dare.  She rarely backed down.  I admired her. 

To me, she always felt like the truth.  The painful, uncomfortable and desperately needed truth. 

Rest in power beautiful soul. 
#sineadoconnor #nothingcompares2u

Heartbroken that we’ve lost our dear Paul Reubens.  He was a top tier human in every way.  Yes, he was a comedic genius but he was also one of the most thoughtful people I’ve ever known.  He lived to make others happy. 

When he invited me to join his iconic film world of Pee-wee Herman I felt like the most fortunate person in the world.  Working with him I got to experience how much he cared about his art and every finely tuned nuance within the world he created.  That world beautifully reflected his extraordinarily unique imagination and desire to entertain. 

Once Paul brought you in he never let you go.  He never missed a holiday or birthday and he always went above and beyond to shower his friends in love. 

Rest sweet friend. 🙏💔@peeweeherman #PaulReubens

If, like me, you believe that every bear still trapped on Vietnam’s bile farms deserve a safe and loving home, please sign the Moon Bear Pledge, and ask your friends to sign too!  You can be a part of the incredible work @animalsasia is doing. 

Bears on bile farms are kept in tiny cages and have bile cruelty extracted from their gallbladder repeatedly over decades.  The more names on this pledge, the louder the message: it’s time to end bear bile farming in Vietnam.  Bear bile farming has no place in the modern world.  Please help Animals Asia rescue every last bear still trapped on a farm and add your name to this pledge. 👇👇

http://bit.ly/moonbear-pledge 

#nobearleftbehind #animalsasia #moonbearpledge

Kathryn Hunter’s performance as the Witches in “The Tragedy Of Macbeth” has stayed with me since I first watched the film in 2021. A vastly underrated performance; her unnatural movements and possessed-looking expression glues you to every frame she’s in. 

Throughout Hunter’s career, she’s gravitated toward male roles in classical plays because they were more complex and fully developed parts. She’s received wide acclaim as the title character in “King Lear,” “Richard III,” “Timon of Athens” and “Cyrano de Bergerac,” as well as Puck in “A Midsummer Night’s Dream,” and the Fool in another production of “Lear.”

🎬 “The Tragedy Of Macbeth” (2021) Dir. Joel Coen.

Sharing this gem from @iamchrispierce celebrating the beautiful existence of Sidney Poitier and all he stood for.  If you haven’t already checked out the album ‘Let All Who Will’, I can’t recommend it enough. 
REPOST:
Sidney Poitier February 20, 1927 – January 6, 2022
“I think about death, but I’m not fearful of it.  I’ve reduced the concept of my existence by saying, ‘I truly, truly try to be better tomorrow than I was today.’ And I mean ‘better’ as simply a better human being, not a better actor, not a better anything, but just a better human being.  That will please me well.  And when I die, I will not be afraid of having lived.” – Sidney Poitier
‘Sidney Poitier’
Song written by Chris Pierce & Mark Malone
From the full-length album ‘Let All Who Will’ 
Produced by Niko Bolas & Dave Resnik
Giant thanks to Mathieu Bitton for graciously passing along images of Sidney Poitier from his personal archives to include.
